1
00:00:00,230 --> 00:00:05,600
In this video we are going to learn Saga pattern for distributed transactions.

2
00:00:06,290 --> 00:00:12,710
The saga pattern is provided to manage data consistency across microservices in distributed transaction

3
00:00:12,710 --> 00:00:13,400
cases.

4
00:00:14,300 --> 00:00:21,260
Basically, Saga pattern offers to create a set of transactions that update microservices sequentially

5
00:00:21,260 --> 00:00:25,940
and publish events to trigger the next transaction for the next microservices.

6
00:00:27,590 --> 00:00:33,830
If one of the step is failed, then Saga pattern trigger to rollback transactions, which is basically

7
00:00:33,830 --> 00:00:38,690
do reverse operations with publishing rollback events to the previous microservices.

8
00:00:39,650 --> 00:00:44,570
By this way, it is managed distributed transactions across microservices.

9
00:00:44,930 --> 00:00:51,080
As you know that it is used some principles inside of the saga pattern like publish subscribe pattern

10
00:00:51,080 --> 00:00:54,470
with brokers or API composition patterns.

11
00:00:56,150 --> 00:01:02,090
The saga pattern is a way to manage long running transactions that involve multiple microservices.

12
00:01:02,720 --> 00:01:09,650
It is based on the idea of the saga, which is a series of local transactions that work together to

13
00:01:09,650 --> 00:01:11,360
achieve end to end use cases.

14
00:01:12,230 --> 00:01:18,890
The Saga pattern is especially useful in distributed systems where multiple microservices need to coordinate

15
00:01:18,890 --> 00:01:19,880
their actions.

16
00:01:21,350 --> 00:01:23,180
For distributed transactions.

17
00:01:23,180 --> 00:01:30,230
The Saga pattern can help to ensure that the overall transaction is either completed successfully or

18
00:01:30,230 --> 00:01:36,260
is rolled back to its initial state if any individual microservice encounters any error.

19
00:01:37,260 --> 00:01:43,740
In order to use Saga patterns in a distributed transactions, we can use a compensating transaction

20
00:01:43,740 --> 00:01:48,540
to undo the changes made by each microservices in the event of an error.

21
00:01:49,080 --> 00:01:55,800
By this way, we can ensure that the overall transaction is either completed successfully or roll back

22
00:01:55,800 --> 00:01:57,420
to its initial state.

23
00:01:59,240 --> 00:02:06,050
The Saga pattern provides transaction management with using a sequence of local transactions of microservices.

24
00:02:06,200 --> 00:02:13,220
Every microservices has its own database, and it can able to manage local transactions in atomic way

25
00:02:13,220 --> 00:02:14,960
with strong consistency.

26
00:02:15,560 --> 00:02:23,750
So Saga pattern grouping these local transactions and sequentially invoking one by one each local transaction

27
00:02:23,750 --> 00:02:28,910
updates the database and publishes an event to the trigger the next local transaction.

28
00:02:29,630 --> 00:02:35,450
If one of the step is failed, then Saga pattern trigger to rollback transactions that are a set of

29
00:02:35,450 --> 00:02:42,140
compensating transaction that rollback the changes on previous microservices and restore the data consistency.

30
00:02:43,830 --> 00:02:49,920
Here you can see the an example of how the Saga pattern could be used in e-commerce application for

31
00:02:49,920 --> 00:02:53,340
order fulfillment process to handle the rollback scenario.

32
00:02:54,090 --> 00:03:00,030
First of all, the customer placed an order on the e-commerce website and provides their payment information.

33
00:03:00,240 --> 00:03:06,150
The application order fulfillment microservices begins a local transaction and send a request to the

34
00:03:06,150 --> 00:03:12,330
inventory of microservices, asking it to reserve the item in the customer's order and the inventory.

35
00:03:12,330 --> 00:03:19,200
Microservice begins a local transaction and reserves the item in the customer's order and the inventory.

36
00:03:19,200 --> 00:03:25,110
Microservices send a response back to the order fulfillment microservices indicating that the items

37
00:03:25,110 --> 00:03:26,580
were reserved successfully.

38
00:03:27,180 --> 00:03:28,830
The order fulfillment process.

39
00:03:28,830 --> 00:03:31,680
Microservices receives the response from the inventory.

40
00:03:31,680 --> 00:03:38,100
Microservices and assuming everything went as planned and it charges the customer payment method and

41
00:03:38,100 --> 00:03:40,500
commits its local transaction.

42
00:03:41,130 --> 00:03:47,520
However, if an error are encountered along the way, the saga pattern provides a way to roll back to

43
00:03:47,520 --> 00:03:49,980
changes made by each microservices.

44
00:03:50,010 --> 00:03:55,980
For example, if the inventory microservice encountered any problem while resolving the items in the

45
00:03:55,980 --> 00:04:00,450
customer order, it could send a failure response back to the order fulfillment.

46
00:04:00,450 --> 00:04:01,440
Microservices.

47
00:04:01,470 --> 00:04:08,130
In this case, the order fulfillment microservices would execute a compensating transaction in order

48
00:04:08,130 --> 00:04:12,750
to undo the chart's operation for customer payment method and cancel the order.

49
00:04:12,780 --> 00:04:16,860
That means it is rolling back to the entire fulfillment process.

50
00:04:16,860 --> 00:04:22,500
As a result, the Saga pattern is useful tool for managing distributed transactions in microservice

51
00:04:22,500 --> 00:04:23,430
architectures.

52
00:04:23,460 --> 00:04:30,180
It allows us to ensure that the overall transaction is either completed successfully or is rollback

53
00:04:30,180 --> 00:04:36,750
to the initial state, so this will provide a resilient and reliable distributed systems when it comes

54
00:04:36,750 --> 00:04:38,760
to applying to end to end use cases.

